    <title>MA112 College Algebra</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
        MA112 College Algebra reviews and strengthens a studentâ€™s 
        algebraic skills in preparation for MA130 Functions. Although it 
        counts as the Rivier University general education mathematics core 
        requirement, the Mathematics Program does not recommend MA112 as a final mathematics course. In 
        addition, MA112 is typically 
        not accepted for transfer at other colleges. You should only enroll
        in MA112 if you are considering taking MA130 Functions in the future.
    </p>
    
    <p>
        Topics include solving linear and polynomial equations and inequalities, 
        simplifying and evaluating polynomial, rational, radical, piecewise-defined, 
        exponential and logarithmic expressions, graphing linear and quadratic functions, 
        and solving applied problems and systems of linear equations. 
    </p>
    
    </introduction>
    <exercises>
        <title>What will I learn in MA112 College Algebra</title>
        <introduction>
          <p> 
            At the end of MA112, you should be able to do the following:
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise>
        <title> Simplify Algebraic Expressions</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Simplify the following:
          </p>
          <ol cols="2">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  3x^2-5(x+4)^2
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  \frac{6x^2-6}{2x^2-4x+4}
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            a. <m>-2x^2-40x-80</m>; (b) <m>\frac{3(x+1)}{x-1}</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <title>Solve Linear and Quadratic Equations</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Solve each of the following:
            </p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>4x-\frac{2}{3}(x+3)=\frac{1}{3}(x-12)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(x-4)(x+5)=36</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              (a) <m>x=-2</m>; (b) <m>x=7</m> or <m>x=-8</m>
            </p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <title>Work with exponents and radicals</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Simplify the following expressions:
            </p>
            <ol cols="3">
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\left(\frac{2x}{3}\right)^3 \left(\frac{9y^2}{14x^5}\right)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\sqrt{9x^2 y^6}</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\left(\frac{24x^8}{15x^3}\right)^{-2}</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              (a) <m>\frac{4y^2}{21x^2}</m>; (b) <m>3xy^3</m>; 
              (c) <m>\frac{25}{64x^{10}}</m>
            </p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <title>Determine an Equation for a Line</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Determine an equation for the line that passes through the point
              <m>(10,4)</m> and is perpendicular to the line <m>y=5x-12</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              Possible solutions include <m>y=-\frac{1}{5}x+6</m> and <m>x+5y=30</m>.
            </p>
          </answer>
          <solution>
            <p>
              In order for the line to be perpendicular to <m>y=5x-12</m>, the 
              slope of the line must be <m>-\frac{1}{5}</m>. We can then use this slope 
              together with the point <m>(10,4)</m> to find the 
              <m>y</m>-intercept by solving <m>4=-\frac{1}{5}(10)+b</m>. Another option 
              is to substitute into the point-slope form to get, <m>y-4=-\frac{1}{5}(x-10)</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <title>Solve systems of linear equations</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Find the ordered pair that satisfies the system:
              <md>
                <mrow> x+2y&amp;=25</mrow>
                <mrow> 10x+15y&amp;=210 </mrow>
              </md>
            </p>

          </statement>
          <answer>  
            <p>
              <m>(x,y)=(9,8)</m>; that is, <m>x=9</m> and <m>y=8</m>.
            </p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <title>Factor polynomials and solve polynomial equations</title>
          <statement> 
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Factor <m>28x^3y^5-14x^5y^2</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Solve <m>81x^4=16</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              (a) <m>14x^3y^2(2y^3-x^2)</m>; (b) <m>x=\pm\frac{2}{3}</m>
            </p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <title>Combine and evaluate functions</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let <m>f(x)=x+3</m> and <m>g(x)=2x^2-x+4</m>. Determine the following:
            </p>
            <ol cols="2">
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>g(10)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(f+g)(x)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(fg)(2)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>g\circ f(x)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              (a) <m>g(10)=194</m>; (b) <m>(f+g)(x)=2x^2+7</m>;
              (c) <m>(fg)(2)=50</m>; (d) <m>f\circ g(x)==2x^2+11x+19</m>
            </p>
          </answer>
          <solution>
            <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>g(10)=2(10)^2-10+4=200-10+4=194</m>
                </p>
              </li> 
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(f+g)(x)=f(x)+g(x)=(x+3)+(2x^2-x+4)=2x^2+7</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(fg)(2)=f(2)g(2)=5\cdot 10=50</m>
                </p>
              </li> 
              <li>
                <p>
                <m>f\circ g(x)=2(x+3)^2-(x+3)+4
              =2x^2+12x+18-x-3+4=2x^2+11x+19</m>  
                </p>
              </li> 
            </ol>
          </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
